then grow faint,
then disappear altogether.

20
00:02:13,409 --> 00:02:15,809
She could sense the priest
beyond the grate-"

21
00:02:15,849 --> 00:02:18,008
On that
particular Friday afternoon...

22
00:02:18,048 --> 00:02:19,488
Last February...

23
00:02:19,568 --> 00:02:22,448
I was reading a story to
my advanced writer's workshop...

24
00:02:22,528 --> 00:02:25,447
by one James Leer,
junior Lit major...

25
00:02:25,527 --> 00:02:28,647
and sole inhabitant
of his own gloomy gulag.

26
00:02:28,727 --> 00:02:30,807
"She bit the flesh of her lip...

27
00:02:30,847 --> 00:02:33,446
closed her eyes, mute."

28
00:02:37,366 --> 00:02:41,565
James' stories were
about as sunny as his disposition.

29
00:02:41,645 --> 00:02:43,725
I was distracted.

30
00:02:43,805 --> 00:02:45,765
Maybe it had something to do
with the fact...

31
00:02:45,845 --> 00:02:47,764
that my wife
had left me that morning.

32
00:02:47,804 --> 00:02:49,524
So. Anyone?

33
00:02:49,564 --> 00:02:51,844
Maybe not.
Wives had left me before.

34
00:02:51,924 --> 00:02:55,363
- Carrie.
- As usual, James' classmates...

35
00:02:55,443 --> 00:02:57,563
aware of a writer's
inherent vulnerability...

36
00:02:57,643 --> 00:03:01,402
offered their sensitive,
gentle opinions.

37
00:03:01,482 --> 00:03:04,282
I mean, Jesus,
what is it with you Catholics?

38
00:03:04,322 --> 00:03:07,322
All right. All right.

39
00:03:07,402 --> 00:03:09,721
Let's try to be
constructive here, shall we?

40
00:03:11,361 --> 00:03:13,241
Howard, what about you?

41
00:03:13,281 --> 00:03:15,161
I hated it.

42
00:03:15,201 --> 00:03:17,360
His stories make me
want to kill myself.

43
00:03:19,280 --> 00:03:22,080
That's not exactly what I meant
by being constructive, Howard.

44
00:03:25,319 --> 00:03:28,119
Yes, Hannah?

45
00:03:28,159 --> 00:03:30,079
I think maybe we're
missing the point.

46
00:03:30,159 --> 00:03:31,638
Hannah Green.

47
00:03:31,678 --> 00:03:33,918
A talented writer who
rented a room in my house.

48
00:03:33,998 --> 00:03:36,998
I knew her to be
insightful, kind...

49
00:03:37,078 --> 00:03:39,997
and compulsively clad
in red cowboy boots.

50
00:03:40,077 --> 00:03:42,517
I had, in fact, never once
seen her without them.

51
00:03:42,597 --> 00:03:46,796
He respects us enough to forget us,
and... that takes courage.

52
00:03:46,836 --> 00:03:50,636
Well put, Hannah. And a good note
to end on, I think.

53
00:03:50,676 --> 00:03:54,195
Oh, don't forget about
WordFest this weekend.

54
00:03:54,275 --> 00:03:55,835
And those of you who are
driving V.I.P.s...

55
00:03:55,915 --> 00:03:57,235
to the
cocktail party this evening...

56
00:03:57,275 --> 00:03:59,355
should have them
at the chancellor's house...

57
00:03:59,435 --> 00:04:00,954
no later than 5:30.

58
00:04:04,074 --> 00:04:06,714
Thank you for that.
Is he all right?

59
00:04:09,713 --> 00:04:12,673
I think so.
How about you?

60
00:04:12,753 --> 00:04:14,793
Me? Yeah. Why?

61
00:04:16,032 --> 00:04:17,872
Just checking.

62
00:04:22,352 --> 00:04:25,151
Turn off the light, please.

63
00:04:32,670 --> 00:04:35,070
It felt good to be in the car.

64
00:04:35,150 --> 00:04:37,829
Alone.
Where I could clear my head.

65
00:04:42,789 --> 00:04:44,908
Tonight was
the opening of WordFest...

66
00:04:44,988 --> 00:04:47,428
the university's annual
three-day "gabathon"...

67
00:04:47,508 --> 00:04:49,308
for writers and wanna-bes.

68
00:04:49,388 --> 00:04:53,067
My editor, Terry Crabtree,
was flying in for the event.

69
00:04:53,107 --> 00:04:56,947
He alone had championed my
last novel, Arsonist's Daughter...

70
00:04:56,987 --> 00:04:59,626
and its critical success
had put us both on the map.

71
00:04:59,666 --> 00:05:01,786
But that was seven years ago...

72
00:05:01,866 --> 00:05:04,666
and I still hadn't
finished my follow-up.

73
00:05:04,746 --> 00:05:07,105
I knew Terry didn't give
a rat's ass about WordFest.

74
00:05:07,145 --> 00:05:10,265
He was coming to town to get
a look at my long-overdue book.

75
00:05:11,745 --> 00:05:14,664
I had to keep him at bay.

76
00:05:17,384 --> 00:05:20,464
- Ah, Tripp.
- Crabtree, how are you, my friend?

77
00:05:20,504 --> 00:05:23,503
- It's good to see you, Tripp.
- Let me help you with this.

78
00:05:23,543 --> 00:05:25,703
Say hello to my new friend.

79
00:05:25,743 --> 00:05:27,983
- Miss Antonia-
- Sloviak.

80
00:05:28,063 --> 00:05:30,822
Nice to meet you.
This way.

81
00:05:30,862 --> 00:05:33,262
I took the liberty of inviting
Antonia to tonight's festivities.

82
00:05:33,302 --> 00:05:34,742
The more the merrier.

83
00:05:34,822 --> 00:05:36,781
Terry was telling me
about you on the plane.

84
00:05:36,821 --> 00:05:38,221
It was all so interesting.

85
00:05:38,261 --> 00:05:40,181
I was just explaining how
a book comes to be published...

86
00:05:40,261 --> 00:05:42,421
what you do as a writer,
what I do as an editor.

87
00:05:42,501 --> 00:05:46,500
I sweat blood for five years,
and he corrects my spelling.

88
00:05:46,540 --> 00:05:50,060
- That's exactly what he said.
- We know each other pretty well.

89
00:05:50,140 --> 00:05:53,379
And actually,
it's seven years.

90
00:05:53,419 --> 00:05:55,819
You know how many times I've
boarded an airplane just praying...

91
00:05:55,899 --> 00:05:58,978
that some gal like her would be
sitting down beside me?

92
00:05:59,018 --> 00:06:01,098
- She's a transvestite.
- You're stoned.

93
00:06:01,178 --> 00:06:04,338
- She's still a transvestite.
- So, how's the book?

94
00:06:04,418 --> 00:06:07,737
Uh, it's fine.
It's done.

95
00:06:07,817 --> 00:06:11,457
Basically. I got a little tinkering
I've still got to do.

96
00:06:11,497 --> 00:06:12,777
Great!

97
00:06:12,857 --> 00:06:15,016
I was hoping I could get a look
at it sometime over the weekend.

98
00:06:15,056 --> 00:06:17,656
It's gonna be a little tough. I'm
at a critical juncture right now.

99
00:06:17,736 --> 00:06:19,816
I thought you were
just tinkering.

100
00:06:19,896 --> 00:06:23,335
W- Well, I am, but I have little
details I've got to work on.

101
00:06:23,415 --> 00:06:25,415
I'm not gonna pressure you.
I just got off the plane.

102
00:06:25,455 --> 00:06:27,774
I mean, I get pressure.
You know? I get-

103
00:06:27,814 --> 00:06:30,734
Know what I mean?

104
00:06:30,814 --> 00:06:34,494
What the hell in the hootenanny
do you suppose that would be?

105
00:06:34,534 --> 00:06:37,053
That would be a tuba.

106
00:06:40,853 --> 00:06:43,452
You didn't actually
purchase this car, did you?

107
00:06:43,492 --> 00:06:46,692
No, I got it from Jerry Nathan.
He owed me some money.

108
00:06:46,772 --> 00:06:48,692
Ah! He owes God money.

109
00:06:48,772 --> 00:06:51,171
Including my commission
on that faux novel of his.

110
00:06:51,211 --> 00:06:52,651
That perfume you're wearing,
Antonia...

111
00:06:52,731 --> 00:06:54,531
that wouldn't happen
to be Cristalle, would it?

112
00:06:54,611 --> 00:06:56,811
Um, uh, yes, it is.

113
00:06:56,891 --> 00:06:59,650
- How did you know?
- Lucky guess.

114
00:07:00,850 --> 00:07:02,690
The WordFest kickoff party...

115
00:07:02,770 --> 00:07:05,689
was always held at
Sara and Walter Gaskell's house.

116
00:07:05,729 --> 00:07:09,489
She was the chancellor, which
meant she oversaw the university.

117
00:07:09,569 --> 00:07:11,409
Her husband, Dr. Gaskell...

118
00:07:11,489 --> 00:07:13,328
was the chairman
of the English Department...

119
00:07:13,408 --> 00:07:15,808
which meant he oversaw me.

120
00:07:19,607 --> 00:07:21,607
Isn't that a nice greenhouse?

121
00:07:21,687 --> 00:07:24,087
It's Mrs. Gaskell's.
It's her hobby.

122
00:07:24,127 --> 00:07:26,047
I thought you were
Mrs. Gaskell's hobby.

123
00:07:26,127 --> 00:07:28,966
Piss off, will you, Crabs?
I lost a wife today.

124
00:07:29,046 --> 00:07:34,085
You'll find another. She'll be
young, beautiful. They always are.

125
00:07:38,325 --> 00:07:41,085
Oh, hello, everyone.
Terry, good to see you again.

126
00:07:41,165 --> 00:07:44,124
Chancellor.
Don't you look ravishing.

127
00:07:45,804 --> 00:07:49,203
- Oh, oh. Easy.
- I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

128
00:07:49,243 --> 00:07:50,203
It's these goddamn shoes.

129
00:07:50,283 --> 00:07:52,123
I don't know how anyone
can walk in these things.

130
00:07:52,163 --> 00:07:55,003
Practice.

131
00:07:55,083 --> 00:07:58,162
- I don't believe we've met.
- Antonia Sloviak.

132
00:07:58,202 --> 00:08:00,802
Poe.

133
00:08:00,882 --> 00:08:03,322
Poe! Poe!

134
00:08:03,402 --> 00:08:05,241
Poe, stop! Poe!

135
00:08:05,321 --> 00:08:07,321
That wouldn't be
Walter's dog, would it?

136
00:08:07,361 --> 00:08:10,361
- Poe!
- Who's he barking at now?

137
00:08:10,441 --> 00:08:12,760
He's still barking at me.
He's blind.

138
00:08:12,800 --> 00:08:15,160
Stop this.

139
00:08:15,200 --> 00:08:17,080
Honestly.

140
00:08:17,160 --> 00:08:19,279
Excuse me, I need to talk to you
for a second, Chancellor.

141
00:08:19,319 --> 00:08:20,439
I need to talk to you too.

142
00:08:20,519 --> 00:08:23,679
Maybe you could help me take these
coats to the upstairs guest room.

143
00:08:23,759 --> 00:08:26,798
I'd be happy to if I knew where
the upstairs guest room was.

144
00:08:26,878 --> 00:08:28,238
I could show you.

145
00:08:28,278 --> 00:08:30,958
Terry.

146
00:08:30,998 --> 00:08:33,437
Yeah. Oh, yeah.
We'll make ourselves at home.

147
00:08:33,557 --> 00:08:35,757
We'll let Poe show us around.
Thanks.

148
00:08:43,356 --> 00:08:45,956
That's new, isn't it?

149
00:08:46,036 --> 00:08:48,475
Yeah, Walter just
got it back from the framer.

150
00:08:50,675 --> 00:08:52,915
