01:16:28,045 --> 01:16:30,684
And I've been here
all day

1211
01:16:33,804 --> 01:16:36,564
- It's too hot to sleep
- Let's go upstairs.

1212
01:16:36,644 --> 01:16:39,123
- Bad vibes down here.
- Time is runnin' away

1213
01:16:39,203 --> 01:16:43,323
Things must've picked up
after we left, huh, Grady?

1214
01:16:43,403 --> 01:16:49,162
Feel like my soul
has turned into steel

1215
01:16:52,202 --> 01:16:58,281
I've still got the scars
that the sun didn't heal

1216
01:17:02,040 --> 01:17:04,440
There's not even
room enough

1217
01:17:04,520 --> 01:17:06,360
To be anywhere

1218
01:17:10,559 --> 01:17:13,599
- It's not dark yet
- Good night, bro.

1219
01:17:13,639 --> 01:17:16,238
But it's gettin' there

1220
01:18:11,351 --> 01:18:14,110
You've reached
the home of Sara and Walter Gaskell.

1221
01:18:14,190 --> 01:18:17,790
Neither Walter or I
can take your-

1222
01:18:17,830 --> 01:18:20,350
- Hello.
- Walter?

1223
01:18:20,390 --> 01:18:24,189
Grady? Oh, Christ, Grady,
do you know what time it is?

1224
01:18:24,269 --> 01:18:26,989
Yeah. I got, uh, 8:15.

1225
01:18:27,069 --> 01:18:28,908
I don't think
that's right, though.

1226
01:18:28,988 --> 01:18:30,828
It's 3:30, Grady.

1227
01:18:30,908 --> 01:18:32,748
Well, this is important,
Walter.

1228
01:18:32,828 --> 01:18:34,748
Oh?

1229
01:18:34,828 --> 01:18:39,067
I, um-I-

1230
01:18:39,147 --> 01:18:41,907
What is it, Grady?

1231
01:18:41,947 --> 01:18:43,866
I'm in love with your wife.

1232
01:18:46,266 --> 01:18:48,466
Excuse me?

1233
01:18:48,506 --> 01:18:51,905
Sara. I'm in love with her.

1234
01:18:52,025 --> 01:18:54,705
Are you drinking,
Prof. Tripp, right now?

1235
01:18:54,745 --> 01:18:56,905
No.

1236
01:18:56,985 --> 01:19:01,224
Nevertheless, I'd like to see you
in my office Monday morning.

1237
01:19:07,023 --> 01:19:08,863
Oh, boy.

1238
01:19:37,179 --> 01:19:39,819
- Sara, what-
- I tried to call, but...

1239
01:19:39,859 --> 01:19:43,498
it seems there's
something wrong...

1240
01:19:43,538 --> 01:19:45,738
with your phone.

1241
01:19:45,778 --> 01:19:49,617
It appears one of our students
is missing...

1242
01:19:49,697 --> 01:19:53,977
and his parents
found a dead dog in his bed.

1243
01:19:54,057 --> 01:19:56,697
It's my fault. I'm sorry.
I've been trying to tell you-

1244
01:19:56,776 --> 01:20:01,576
I'm not feeling very happy
with you right now.

1245
01:20:01,656 --> 01:20:03,656
And more importantly,
Walter isn't very happy.

1246
01:20:03,736 --> 01:20:05,575
He's gotten the police involved.

1247
01:20:05,615 --> 01:20:09,215
They seem to think James Leer is
somehow responsible for all this.

1248
01:20:09,295 --> 01:20:14,894
You wouldn't happen to know
where James Leer is, would you?

1249
01:20:14,934 --> 01:20:17,134
He's inside.

1250
01:20:17,174 --> 01:20:19,733
And Marilyn's jacket?

1251
01:20:21,453 --> 01:20:23,653
Oh, it's in my car.

1252
01:20:28,332 --> 01:20:30,612
- Somebody stole my car.
- Oh, man!

1253
01:20:30,652 --> 01:20:32,692
Honestly!
Somebody stole my car!

1254
01:20:32,772 --> 01:20:35,051
I parked it right there
last night!

1255
01:20:35,091 --> 01:20:37,171
- Are you sure it was parked there?
- Of course I'm sure! It was-

1256
01:20:37,251 --> 01:20:40,331
Oh, Christ. Here comes
the puberty police now.

1257
01:20:40,371 --> 01:20:43,530
Okay, okay, I'll deal with this.
You go dig up James.

1258
01:20:52,569 --> 01:20:54,489
Is he awake?

1259
01:20:54,609 --> 01:20:58,048
There's a police officer on
the porch, and he's not going away.

1260
01:20:58,128 --> 01:21:01,168
- That same guy?
- Same one.

1261
01:21:01,248 --> 01:21:05,247
No offense, Prof. Tripp,
but you look sort of crappy.

1262
01:21:05,327 --> 01:21:07,847
He's right. I mean,
you do look horrible.

1263
01:21:07,887 --> 01:21:11,686
It's the chancellor.

1264
01:21:11,806 --> 01:21:14,166
- We're fine. We're just fine.
- Fine, right.

1265
01:21:14,246 --> 01:21:17,486
- Fit as a fuckin' fiddle.
- James...

1266
01:21:17,566 --> 01:21:20,245
come on.

1267
01:21:20,325 --> 01:21:24,005
Uh, James,
this book of yours?

1268
01:21:24,045 --> 01:21:27,884
It's... not bad.
It's not bad at all.

1269
01:21:28,004 --> 01:21:31,484
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

1270
01:21:35,683 --> 01:21:37,523
I'm wanna publish this.

1271
01:21:37,603 --> 01:21:41,402
I think with the proper
editorial guidance...

1272
01:21:41,482 --> 01:21:43,362
this could be brilliant.

1273
01:21:43,402 --> 01:21:45,282
Aw, that's great.
That's great.

1274
01:21:45,322 --> 01:21:49,681
Between Officer Pupcik and you,
he can be the next Jean Genet.

1275
01:21:49,801 --> 01:21:52,881
Been a long time since somebody
wrote a really good book in jail.

1276
01:21:52,961 --> 01:21:56,760
Don't you worry, James.
We 're gonna figure something out.

1277
01:21:56,840 --> 01:22:00,440
I'm not worried. You're
not worried, are you, Prof. Tripp?

1278
01:22:00,520 --> 01:22:03,719
I'm a little worried, James.

1279
01:22:03,799 --> 01:22:07,439
Don't be.
I don't care if they expel me.

1280
01:22:07,519 --> 01:22:09,399
I probably should be expelled.

1281
01:22:09,439 --> 01:22:11,438
Well, let's hope
it doesn't come to that.

1282
01:22:14,398 --> 01:22:16,278
Prof. Tripp.

1283
01:22:16,358 --> 01:22:20,117
- Yes, James?
- Even if I end up going to jail...

1284
01:22:20,197 --> 01:22:22,437
you're still the best teacher
I ever had.

1285
01:22:29,156 --> 01:22:31,316
I wonder if this is
what the university has in mind...

1286
01:22:31,396 --> 01:22:34,115
when it promises
a liberal education.

1287
01:22:35,315 --> 01:22:37,515
Walter wouldn't really
press charges, would he?

1288
01:22:37,595 --> 01:22:39,434
We'll know soon enough.

1289
01:22:39,514 --> 01:22:40,434
In a couple of hours...

1290
01:22:40,514 --> 01:22:42,394
he's gonna sit down with
the police and James' parents...

1291
01:22:42,434 --> 01:22:45,354
and he was a wee bit prickly
this morning.

1292
01:22:49,033 --> 01:22:51,673
You didn't happen to call
our house last night, did you?

1293
01:22:51,713 --> 01:22:54,752
I think I might have, yes.

1294
01:22:54,832 --> 01:22:57,672
What do you think
you might have said?

1295
01:22:57,752 --> 01:23:01,311
I think I might have said
I was in love with you.

1296
01:23:03,391 --> 01:23:05,351
He told you.

1297
01:23:05,431 --> 01:23:08,630
- He told me.
- And what did you say?

1298
01:23:08,670 --> 01:23:11,510
I said it didn't
sound like you.

1299
01:23:25,708 --> 01:23:27,988
Hey, Tripp!

1300
01:23:31,187 --> 01:23:33,947
So, what do we do now?

1301
01:23:34,867 --> 01:23:36,707
Find the jacket!

1302
01:23:36,787 --> 01:23:38,866
Exactly how do we do that?

1303
01:23:38,906 --> 01:23:40,906
I've got an idea
where it is.

1304
01:23:40,986 --> 01:23:44,346
We could ask Hannah
if we could borrow her car.

1305
01:23:44,426 --> 01:23:49,385
Sure. Keys are on the desk,
next to your book.

1306
01:23:53,304 --> 01:23:55,224
I didn't finish it.
Fell asleep.

1307
01:23:55,344 --> 01:23:57,784
Oh, it's that good, huh?

1308
01:23:57,864 --> 01:23:59,704
It's not that. It's just-

1309
01:23:59,784 --> 01:24:03,103
It's just... what?

1310
01:24:13,542 --> 01:24:15,141
Grady, you know how in class...

1311
01:24:15,221 --> 01:24:17,341
how you're always telling us
that writers make choices?

1312
01:24:17,421 --> 01:24:19,581
Yeah.

1313
01:24:19,661 --> 01:24:21,981
And even though your book
is really beautiful...

1314
01:24:22,061 --> 01:24:24,660
I mean, amazingly
beautiful, it's-

1315
01:24:25,740 --> 01:24:28,100
It's, at times, it's, uh-

1316
01:24:28,180 --> 01:24:31,979
Very detailed. Uh-

1317
01:24:32,059 --> 01:24:35,419
You know, with the genealogies
of everyone's horses...

1318
01:24:35,499 --> 01:24:38,698
and the dental record s
and so on and-

1319
01:24:38,778 --> 01:24:42,818
And I could be wrong, but it just,
it sort of reads in places like-

1320
01:24:44,337 --> 01:24:46,177
You didn't really
make any choices.

1321
01:24:49,377 --> 01:24:51,257
At all.

1322
01:24:53,216 --> 01:24:56,016
And I was just wondering if
it might not be different if-

1323
01:24:56,056 --> 01:24:58,216
if when you wrote,
you weren't always...

1324
01:25:00,135 --> 01:25:02,135
under the influence.

1325
01:25:09,414 --> 01:25:11,254
Well-

1326
01:25:11,334 --> 01:25:16,693
Well, uh, thank you
for the thought.

1327
01:25:16,733 --> 01:25:19,093
But shocking
as it may sound...

1328
01:25:19,133 --> 01:25:22,732
I am not the first writer
to sip a little weed.

1329
01:25:22,772 --> 01:25:24,652
Furthermore, it might
surprise you to know...

1330
01:25:24,692 --> 01:25:27,092
that one book I wrote as you say
"under the influence"...

1331
01:25:27,132 --> 01:25:30,131
just happened to win a little
something called the PE N Award...

1332
01:25:30,211 --> 01:25:33,291
which, by the way,
I accepted under the influence.

1333
01:25:44,609 --> 01:25:47,809
Hey, let me
help you with that.

1334
01:25:47,889 --> 01:25:50,449
- Don't touch it.
- Okay. I'll drive.

1335
01:25:55,008 --> 01:25:57,968
Let me get this straight.
Jerry Nathan owes you money...

1336
01:25:58,007 --> 01:26:00,127
so as collateral,
he gives you his car.

1337
01:26:00,207 --> 01:26:02,047
Only I'm beginning to think
that the car...

1338
01:26:02,127 --> 01:26:03,967
...wasn't exactly Jerry's to give.

1339
01:26:04,047 --> 01:26:05,886
Ah, so whose car was it?

1340
01:26:05,926 --> 01:26:08,806
- My guess? Vernon Hard apple.
- The hood jumper?

1341
01:26:08,846 --> 01:26:12,606
He said a few things that lead me
to believe that the car was his.

1342
01:26:12,646 --> 01:26:15,245
- Such as?
- "That's my car, motherfucker. "

1343
01:26:17,445 --> 01:26:19,725
All right, so we find Vernon,
we find the car.

1344
01:26:19,805 --> 01:26:22,764
- We find the car-
- We find the jacket.

1345
01:26:32,083 --> 01:26:35,842
Wow. Christ!
How'd you know, Tripp?

1346
01:26:37,482 --> 01:26:39,242
Oh, I don't know.

1347
01:26:39,322 --> 01:26:41,642
- Let's just call it a hunch.
- I call it genius.

1348
01:26:41,682 --> 01:26:45,321
Good to know I'm still
talented at something.

1349
01:26:45,361 --> 01:26:47,721
Careful.

1350
01:26:47,801 --> 01:26:50,560
Keep that motor running.

1351
01:27:45,953 --> 01:27:48,033
I know you.

1352
01:27:49,312 --> 01:27:51,192
Double Dickel
on the rocks.

1353
01:27:53,752 --> 01:27:55,592
Oola.

1354
01:27:55,672 --> 01:27:57,871
I never forget a drink.

1355
01:28:01,711 --> 01:28:05,470
I never forget an Oola.

1356
01:28:05,550 --> 01:28:07,870
Forget me?

1357
01:28:07,910 --> 01:28:10,710
- Vernon?
- Go inside, cupcake. He's got a gun.

1358
01:28:10,749 --> 01:28:14,069
- Who's got a gun?
- You've got a gun! Drop it!

1359
01:28:14,109 --> 01:28:16,789
- Uh-oh.
- Vernon, relax.

1360
01:28:16,829 --> 01:28:19,388
- Why is he calling you Vernon?
- Why is he sitting in my car?

1361
01:28:19,468 --> 01:28:22,748
He's crazy, that's why!
He probably calls everybody Vernon.

1362
01:28:22,788 --> 01:28:24,948
- Now drop that gun!
- Oh, dear.

1363
01:28:24,988 --> 01:28:27,387
It's a souvenir. They don't
even have caps for this thing.

1364
01:28:27,427 --> 01:28:29,347
- It's a souvenir.
- Bullshit!

1365
01:28:29,427 --> 01:28:31,507
I know a gun when I see one,
and that's a gun!

1366
01:28:31,547 --> 01:28:32,866
No! No, really-

1367
01:28:32,946 --> 01:28:34,706
Oh, God! Oh!

1368
01:28:34,746 --> 01:28:37,786
Gimme that gun!
Are you crazy?

1369
01:28:37,866 --> 01:28:41,585
Can't you see the condition
my girl's in? Get out! Get out!

1370
01:28:41,625 --> 01:28:44,665
Hey! Stop!

1371
01:28:44,745 --> 01:28:46,665
Cupcake, you okay?

1372
01:28:46,745 --> 01:28:49,544
Tripp, run!

1373
01:28:49,624 --> 01:28:52,824
Who in the hell is that?

1374
01:28:52,864 --> 01:28:56,823
- Oh, shit!
- Vernon, don 't - No! Don't shoot!

1375
01:28:56,863 --> 01:28:58,943
- Oh, no! Don't!
- Don't shoot!

1376
01:28:59,023 --> 01:29:01,143
Come on, Tripp!
Jump in! Run!

1377
01:29:01,183 --> 01:29:03,582
He's a crazy man.

1378
01:29:14,301 --> 01:29:17,061
Oh, my God.

1379
01:29:30,819 --> 01:29:32,698
I take it back.

1380
01:29:32,738 --> 01:29:35,258
Shoot him.

1381
01:29:39,138 --> 01:29:42,777
Naturally, you have copies.

1382
01:29:42,857 --> 01:29:46,457
I have an alternate version
of the first chapter.

1383
01:29:46,497 --> 01:29:48,216
You'll be all right, then.
Look at-

1384
01:29:48,256 --> 01:29:50,176
Look at Carlyle
when he lost his luggage.

1385
01:29:50,256 --> 01:29:53,296
- That was Macaulay.
- Oh.

1386
01:29:53,336 --> 01:29:56,295
Well, what about Hemingway
when Hadley lost all those stories?

1387
01:29:56,375 --> 01:29:58,935
He was never able
to reproduce them.

1388
01:29:59,095 --> 01:30:02,134
Look, Tripp, I don't wanna
depreciate the loss here...

1389
01:30:02,214 --> 01:30:05,814
but maybe, you know,
in a sense, it's for the best.

1390
01:30:05,934 --> 01:30:08,773
You suggesting
it's some kind of sign?

1391
01:30:08,853 --> 01:30:10,853
- In a sense.
- In my experience...

1392
01:30:10,933 --> 01:30:13,173
signs are usually
a little more subtle.

1393
01:30:13,293 --> 01:30:16,572
Let me get this straight. All that
paper that blew away back there...

1394
01:30:16,692 --> 01:30:18,572
that was the only copy?

1395
01:30:18,652 --> 01:30:20,532
I'm afraid so, yes.

1396
01:30:20,572 --> 01:30:24,691
And you, you're saying
that it's some kind of a sign?

1397
01:30:24,771 --> 01:30:26,611
Man, what in the fuck
the matter with you?

1398
01:30:26,691 --> 01:30:28,531
Don't.

1399
01:30:28,611 --> 01:30:32,410
All I'm saying is that
sometimes, subconsciously...

1400
01:30:32,530 --> 01:30:34,530
a person will put themselves
in a situation...

1401
01:30:34,610 --> 01:30:36,850
perhaps even create
that situation...

1402
01:30:36,970 --> 01:30:40,689
in order to have an arena in which
to work out an unresolved issue.

1403
01:30:40,769 --> 01:30:43,409
It's a covert way, if you will,
of addressing a problem.

1404
01:30:43,529 --> 01:30:45,369
I'll tell you
the problem.

1405
01:30:45,449 --> 01:30:48,248
You behind the wheel,
there's your problem.

1406
01:30:48,328 --> 01:30:51,128
Did you or did you not
have a gun to his head?

1407
01:30:51,208 --> 01:30:53,807
- Watch the road, please.
- He was trying to steal my car.

1408
01:30:53,927 --> 01:30:55,967
Did you or did you not
have a gun to his head?

1409
01:30:56,047 --> 01:30:57,807
All right! All right!

1410
01:30:57,927 --> 01:30:59,767
That's enough!
That is enough!

1411
01:30:59,847 --> 01:31:03,806
What is done is done! I don't
wanna hear about it anymore, okay?

1412
01:31:18,524 --> 01:31:21,404
So what was it about,
your book?

1413
01:31:23,403 --> 01:31:25,803
What was the story?

1414
01:31:27,803 --> 01:31:29,683
I don't know.

1415
01:31:29,763 --> 01:31:31,002
What he means is...

1416
01:31:31,082 --> 01:31:33,522
it's difficult to distill
the essence of a book sometimes...

1417
01:31:33,642 --> 01:31:35,402
because it lives in the mind.

1418
01:31:35,522 --> 01:31:37,481
But you got to know
what it was about, right?

1419
01:31:37,601 --> 01:31:40,921
If you didn't know what it
was about, why were you writing it?

1420
01:31:44,521 --> 01:31:46,400
I couldn't stop.

1421
01:31:57,119 --> 01:31:58,959
Vernon, can I
ask you a question?

1422
01:32:02,558 --> 01:32:04,398
Boy or girl?

1423
01:32:10,277 --> 01:32:13,837
As long as it looks like her...

1424
01:32:13,957 --> 01:32:16,356
- I really don't care.
- You-

1425
01:32:16,436 --> 01:32:18,316
You know what I'm saying?

1426
01:32:18,396 --> 01:32:20,316
Yeah.

1427
01:32:21,795 --> 01:32:23,675
- Thanks for the ride, Vernon.
- Anytime.

1428
01:32:23,715 --> 01:32:26,115
- And another thing.
- Yeah?

1429
01:32:26,155 --> 01:32:29,234
- Stop calling me Vernon.
- Okay.

1430
01:32:29,314 --> 01:32:32,714
- Jacket, Tripp.
- What?

1431
01:32:32,834 --> 01:32:34,994
We need the jacket.

1432
01:32:35,074 --> 01:32:37,153
Oh, right.

1433
01:32:40,993 --> 01:32:42,873
Oola, about that jacket-

1434
01:32:42,913 --> 01:32:44,952
Yeah.

1435
01:32:45,032 --> 01:32:47,152
It used to belong
to Marilyn Monroe.

1436
01:32:48,752 --> 01:32:50,592
- Really?
- Mm-hmm.

1437
01:32:50,672 --> 01:32:52,951
She had small shoulders...

1438
01:32:53,031 --> 01:32:55,191
just like you.

1439
01:32:55,271 --> 01:32:57,471
A lot of people
don't know that.

1440
01:32:59,230 --> 01:33:01,710
Thank you.

1441
01:33:01,790 --> 01:33:05,150
Man, that book of yours
must have been one nutty ride.

1442
01:33:05,230 --> 01:33:07,349
Come on, baby. Let's go.

1443
01:33:19,108 --> 01:33:21,507
Would you mind explaining to me
what you just did?

1444
01:33:21,547 --> 01:33:23,547
Came to my senses.

1445
01:33:23,627 --> 01:33:26,787
Oh. Congratulations. Meanwhile,
what's James supposed to do?

1446
01:33:26,907 --> 01:33:28,746
Pray that Walter Gaskell
comes to his?

1447
01:33:28,826 --> 01:33:32,146
Walter Gaskell doesn't wanna
send James Leer to jail.

1448
01:33:32,226 --> 01:33:34,106
He's up in his office
right now.

1449
01:33:34,146 --> 01:33:37,185
