1471
01:34:38,737 --> 01:34:41,257
You're pretty good at that.

1472
01:34:45,896 --> 01:34:47,736
Tripp.

1473
01:34:51,775 --> 01:34:53,655
I'm sorry.

1474
01:35:05,373 --> 01:35:07,253
Improvise.

1475
01:35:07,413 --> 01:35:10,373
As for me,
I was through improvising.

1476
01:35:10,453 --> 01:35:14,572
I knew what I had to do.
I had to find Sara.

1477
01:35:14,652 --> 01:35:18,931
I had to convince her
that she was my choice...

1478
01:35:18,971 --> 01:35:21,811
that, in fact, she had been
from the very beginning.

1479
01:35:31,250 --> 01:35:36,689
And now, as those of you who've been
with us in previous years know...

1480
01:35:36,769 --> 01:35:39,769
we have a tradition of sorts
here at WordFest.

1481
01:35:39,889 --> 01:35:42,568
I'm speaking, of course,
of the Plums...

1482
01:35:42,648 --> 01:35:44,568
those fortunate local writers...

1483
01:35:44,688 --> 01:35:47,608
who have successfully
placed their manuscripts...

1484
01:35:47,728 --> 01:35:51,007
with visiting publishers'
representatives.

1485
01:35:51,127 --> 01:35:53,927
This weekend, Susan Lowery
of North Braddock...

1486
01:35:53,967 --> 01:35:56,806
found a publisher
for her children's book...

1487
01:35:56,846 --> 01:35:58,206
The Loneliest Prawn.

1488
01:35:58,286 --> 01:36:02,925
Stand up, Susan.

1489
01:36:11,084 --> 01:36:16,644
No w, this next one is, I think,
very exciting to announce...

1490
01:36:16,684 --> 01:36:20,323
because it concerns
a student here at the university.

1491
01:36:20,363 --> 01:36:22,323
Our own James Leer...

1492
01:36:22,403 --> 01:36:25,562
sophomore
in English Literature...

1493
01:36:25,642 --> 01:36:29,042
has found a publisher
for his first novel...

1494
01:36:29,122 --> 01:36:33,401
which I believe is called...
"The Lovely Parade."

1495
01:36:35,441 --> 01:36:38,321
- Love Parade.
- Love Parade.

1496
01:36:38,401 --> 01:36:42,640
- James?
- Stand up. Go on.

1497
01:36:45,000 --> 01:36:48,239
He's a real alien probe,
if you know what I mean.

1498
01:36:48,319 --> 01:36:51,119
Take a bow, James!

1499
01:37:16,875 --> 01:37:19,875
Wonder boy.

1500
01:37:26,074 --> 01:37:31,473
And finally, and perhaps
not least importantly...

1501
01:37:31,553 --> 01:37:35,713
Terry Crabtree of Bartizan has also
decided to publish my own book...

1502
01:37:35,793 --> 01:37:39,872
a critical exploration of
the union of Joe DiMaggio...

1503
01:37:39,912 --> 01:37:41,792
and Marilyn Monroe...

1504
01:37:41,832 --> 01:37:44,712
and its function
in American mythopoetics...

1505
01:37:44,792 --> 01:37:47,951
which, tentatively,
I have entitled...

1506
01:37:48,031 --> 01:37:50,791
The Last American Marriage.

1507
01:37:50,831 --> 01:37:55,790
So, until next year,
thank you, everyone.

1508
01:38:14,748 --> 01:38:16,227
Grady, I took another look...

1509
01:38:16,307 --> 01:38:18,027
at The Arsonist's Daughter
the other night.

1510
01:38:18,107 --> 01:38:21,027
That description of the bald
cypress left me breathless.

1511
01:38:21,107 --> 01:38:23,306
Thanks, Q.
I appreciate that.

1512
01:38:48,143 --> 01:38:50,143
Sara!

1513
01:39:25,378 --> 01:39:27,258
Yo, Traxler.

1514
01:39:30,417 --> 01:39:33,857
